Exercise: Conduct Your First Ritual Autopsy

Choose one individual in your field whose consistent performance you respect. Not a distant celebrity CEO, but someone you can observe somewhat closely—a colleague, a manager, an industry peer with a transparent process (e.g., through a blog, podcast, or talks). Your mission is to hypothesize their keystone rituals.

Step 1: Gather Intelligence.
Look for clues in their output. Do they release work at consistent times? Is there a particular depth or format to their communication? Listen for offhand comments. “Oh, I always sketch on paper first.” “I block my first hour for deep work every day.” “I have a Friday shutdown process where I review the week.” These are gold.

Step 2: Apply the Five Whys to an Outcome.
Pick one specific, admirable outcome. Example: “They never seem overwhelmed by inbox chaos.”
Why? They process email efficiently.
Why? They have a system for triage.
Why? They batch it at specific times.
Why? They use a tool to enforce batching (e.g., inbox closed except at 11am & 4pm).
Why? Their keystone morning ritual includes planning those batch times, so the decision is made in calm, not in reaction.

Step 3: Hypothesize the Keystone.
Based on your digging, propose one or two small, specific, repeatable actions that might be their catalytic domino. Write them in mechanical terms:
“Trigger: Upon sitting at desk. Action: Open blank notepad, write today’s date and ‘Top 3.’ Complete before opening any digital device.Intent: Force priority clarity before the world intrudes.”
“Trigger: Completion of a work block. Action: Stand, walk to window, look at farthest point for 60 seconds, note one physical sensation (e.g., ‘feel of air on skin’). Intent: Sensory reset to prevent cognitive carryover and eye strain.”

Step 4: Distinguish Ritual from Routine.
Ask: Is this action likely done with autopilot or deliberate intent? What sensory details (a specific notebook, a particular chair, a taste, a sound) might they incorporate to create presence? If you can’t find evidence, design a plausible one. This builds your ritual-thinking muscle.
